-- BNP Paribas, Natixis, Societe Generale May Move: French Equity Preview
-- Adria Cimino
-- 2010-06-15T06:31:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-15/euromedis-faiveley-faurecia-and-francois-freres-french-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may have unusual changes in Paris. Symbols are in
parentheses after company names and prices are from the last
close.  
 June futures on France’s CAC 40 Index lost 28 to 3,595.5 at
8:12 a.m. in Paris.  
 The CAC 40 rose 2 percent to 3,626.04 yesterday. The SBF
120 Index gained 1.9 percent.  
 BNP Paribas SA  (BNP FP) and  Societe Generale SA  (GLE FP):
Societe Generale and BNP Paribas are among banks considering a
bid for Allied Irish Banks Plc’s stake in Bank Zachodni WBK SA
of Poland valued at about $3 billion, according to three people
with knowledge of the matter. Separately, Societe Generale said
it’s aiming for net income of around 6 billion euros ($7.3
billion) in 2012, driven by growth at its corporate and
investment bank and in Russia. BNP climbed 2.7 percent to 47.50
euros. Societe Generale advanced 3.9 percent to 35.05 euros.  
 Euromedis Groupe  (EMG FP): The distributor of medical
supplies said profit this fiscal year will be close to the level
reported for the year ending July 31, 2008. The shares fell 5.5
percent to 4.26 euros.  
 Faiveley Transport  (LEY FP): The railroad-equipment maker
said net profit in the year ended March 31 rose 38 percent and
it plans to raise the dividend by 20 percent. Sales this year
will be stable, with a “substantial” increase in following
years, it said. The shares rose 1.2 percent to 55.46 euros.  
 Faurecia SA  (EO FP): The car-parts maker’s stock movements
are being examined by France’s AMF market watchdog after the
company gave a series of presentations to analysts in Paris.
Officials at the Autorite des Marches Financiers are looking at
the reasons for an increase of as much as 6 percent in the share
price and how that relates to the company’s financial
communication during its investor day, AMF spokeswoman  Christine Anglade  said by telephone. The shares advanced 5 percent to
14.83 euros.  
 Natixis SA  (KN FP): The bank doesn’t need to raise new
capital to meet Basel 3 requirements, Chief Executive Officer
 Laurent Mignon  told French daily La Tribune in an interview. The
stock increased 2 percent to 3.68 euros.  
 PSA Peugeot Citroen  (UG FP) and  Renault SA  (RNO FP):
European new-car sales declined 8.7 percent in May to 1,164,994
vehicles, the ACEA industry group said. January through May
registrations increased 2.3 percent, the ACEA said. Peugeot,
Europe’s second-largest carmaker, gained 3.6 percent to 22.20
euros. Renault, France’s second-biggest, climbed 2.7 percent to
31.45 euros.  
 Tonnellerie Francois Freres  (TFF FP): The maker of wine
barrels said revenue for the fiscal year fell 2.9 percent to
109.5 million euros. The shares dropped 1 cent to 29.74 euros.  
